\vspace{-10pt}
\begin{tabbing}
\phantom{References: }\= \\
To: \>Bill\\
Subject: \>Alternative minimum $\zeta$ calculation\\
From: \>Van Snyder\\
\end{tabbing}

\parindent 0pt \parskip 6pt
\vspace{-20pt}

We have $H$ tabulated on a $(\phi,\zeta)$ grid.  (Below, I assume $\phi$ means
$\phi - \phi_t$.)  We could in principle approximate $H(\phi,\zeta)$ using a
bicubic spline, but for simplicity, within the grid cell having a lower left
corner $(\phi_i,\zeta_j)$ approximate it instead by the bilinear function

\begin{equation}\label{H}
H(\phi,\zeta) = H(\phi_i,\zeta_j) +
 a(\phi-\phi_i) + b(\zeta-\zeta_j) + c\,(\phi-\phi_i)(\zeta-\zeta_j)
\end{equation}

Since we want $H(\phi,\zeta)$ to interpolate the corners of the grid cell
exactly, we have

\begin{equation}\begin{split}
a =\,& \frac{H(\phi_{i+1},\zeta_j)-H(\phi_i,\zeta_j)}{\phi_{i+1}-\phi_i}
  \approx \frac{\partial H}{\partial \phi}\\
b =\,& \frac{H(\phi_i,\zeta_{j+1})-H(\phi_i,\zeta_j)}{\zeta_{j+1}-\zeta_j}
  \approx \frac{\partial H}{\partial \zeta}\\
c =\,& \frac{H(\phi_{i+1},\zeta_{j+1})-H(\phi_{i+1},\zeta_j) -
             H(\phi_i,\zeta_{j+1})-H(\phi_i,\zeta_j)}
            {(\phi_{i+1}-\phi_i)(\zeta_{j+1}-\zeta_j)}
  \approx \frac{\partial^2 H}{\partial \phi \partial \zeta}
\end{split}\end{equation}

Solving Equation (\ref{H}) for $\zeta$ within the $(i,j)$ grid cell, we have

\begin{equation}
\zeta = \frac{H(\phi,\zeta)-H(\phi_i,\zeta_j) + a \phi}{b + c \phi}
\end{equation}

Substituting the line of sight $H(\phi,\zeta) = H_t \sec \phi$ were $H_t$ is the
tangent height we have

\begin{equation}\label{zeta}
\zeta = \frac{H_t \sec \phi - H(\phi_i,\zeta_j) + a \phi}{b + c \phi}
\end{equation}

\renewcommand{\d}{\text{d}}

Setting $\frac{\d \zeta}{\d \phi}=0$ and taking the numerator, we need to solve

\begin{equation}
(c \phi + b) H_t \sin \phi + (c H(\phi_i,\zeta_j) + a b ) \cos^2 \phi
 -c H_t \cos \phi = 0
\end{equation}

for $\phi_i\leq\phi\leq\phi_{i+1}$, from which Equation (\ref{zeta}) gives us
the minimum $\zeta$.  Since $\zeta_i < \zeta_{i+1}$, this solution is
interesting only if $\zeta < \zeta_i$.  Since the minimum $\zeta$ is unlikely
to occur far from the tangent, we only need to consider $\phi_{i-1} < \phi <
\phi_{i+1}$ where we choose $i$ to maximize the minimum of
$\{\phi_t-\phi_{i-1}, \phi_{i+1}-\phi_t\}$ where $\phi_t$ is the tangent
$\phi$, unless $\phi_t \approx \frac12 (\phi_i+\phi_{i+1})$ for some $i$, in
which case we may need to consider $\phi_{i-1} < \phi < \phi_{i+2}$ if
$\phi_{i+1}-\phi_i$ is small, or only $\phi_i < \phi < \phi_{i+1}$ if
$\phi_{i+1}-\phi_i$ is large.

